## Pages Specification
## Page Navigation Flow

The Storycatcher II application guides users through a clear set of pages, facilitating secure access, interactive story capture, and efficient management of personal narratives. The navigation flow emphasizes a user-centric design, allowing seamless transitions between core functionalities while maintaining privacy and data integrity.

```mermaid
graph TD
    subgraph "Public / Unauthenticated Access"
        LP["Landing Page"] --> LGP("Login Page");
        LP --> RP("Registration Page");
        LP --> PAP("Public Archive Page");
    end

    subgraph "Authenticated User Flow"
        LGP --> MSP("My Stories Page");
        RP --> MSP;
        MSP --> SCP("Story Capture Page");
        MSP --> SDSP("Story Detail / Edit Page");
        MSP --> LGP;
        SCP --> MSP;
        SDSP --> MSP;
        SDSP --> ESOP("Export / Share Options");
        ESOP --> SDSP;
        ESOP --> MSP;
    end

    subgraph "Public Story Viewing"
        PAP --> PSVP("Public Story View Page");
        PSVP --> PAP;
    end

    style LP fill:#f0f8ff,stroke:#3178c6,stroke-width:2px
    style LGP fill:#e0f7fa,stroke:#00796b,stroke-width:2px
    style RP fill:#e0f7fa,stroke:#00796b,stroke-width:2px
    style MSP fill:#c8e6c9,stroke:#388e3c,stroke-width:2px
    style SCP fill:#fff3e0,stroke:#e65100,stroke-width:2px
    style SDSP fill:#fffde7,stroke:#fbc02d,stroke-width:2px
    style ESOP fill:#ffe0b2,stroke:#fb8c00,stroke-width:2px
    style PAP fill:#e3f2fd,stroke:#1e88e5,stroke-width:2px
    style PSVP fill:#e3f2fd,stroke:#1e88e5,stroke-width:2px
```

**Overview of Page Hierarchy and User Flow:**
The application's navigation is structured around two primary states: unauthenticated and authenticated. The `Landing Page` is the initial entry, directing users to `Login`, `Registration`, or the `Public Archive`. Authenticated users access the `My Stories Page` dashboard, from which they can initiate `Story Capture`, manage stories via `Story Detail / Edit Page`, or `Logout`. The `Story Capture Page` is for interactive audio recording. The `Story Detail / Edit Page` allows metadata management and initiates `Export / Share Options`, including GDPR consent. Publicly shared stories are accessible via the `Public Archive Page` and individual `Public Story View Pages` for all users.

## Page Specifications

### Landing Page
*   **Purpose**: Initial entry point, overview, directs to registration, login, or public archive.
*   **Key Content**: Branding, brief description, calls to action for registration, login, public stories.
*   **Navigation**: To `Registration Page`, `Login Page`, `Public Archive Page`.

### Registration Page
*   **Purpose**: Allows new users to create an account (Requirement 2285).
*   **Key Content**: Form fields (username, email, password, confirmation), privacy policy link, terms of service checkbox.
*   **Navigation**: From `Landing Page`; To `My Stories Page` (on success), `Login Page`. Displays error feedback (Requirement 2298).

### Login Page
*   **Purpose**: Enables existing users to securely log in (Requirement 2285).
*   **Key Content**: Form fields (username/email, password), "Forgot Password" link (future).
*   **Navigation**: From `Landing Page`, `Registration Page`; To `My Stories Page` (on success), `Registration Page`. Displays error feedback (Requirement 2298).

### My Stories Page
*   **Purpose**: User's dashboard for viewing, editing, managing stories (Requirement 2292, 2289).
*   **Key Content**: List of archived stories (titles, summaries, dates), sort/filter options. Displays confirmation for archived stories (part of 2288).
*   **Navigation**: From `Login Page`, `Registration Page`, `Story Capture Page`, `Story Detail / Edit Page`; To `Story Capture Page`, `Story Detail / Edit Page`, `Login Page` (on logout). Supports offline-first display (Requirement 2289).

### Story Capture Page
*   **Purpose**: Interactive interface for recording audio, displaying AI-guided questions, transcription/analysis (Requirement 2288).
*   **Key Content**: Microphone access prompt/status (Requirement 2300), recording controls (start, stop, pause), real-time/near real-time transcript (Requirement 2287), AI-generated guiding questions (Requirement 2286), segment summary. UI states for idle, recording, processing, showing analysis (Requirement 2288).
*   **Navigation**: From `My Stories Page`; To `My Stories Page` (on finalizing story). Displays robust error handling and UI feedback (Requirement 2298).

### Story Detail / Edit Page
*   **Purpose**: View full transcript/summary, edit metadata, initiate export/sharing (Requirement 2292, 2291, 2293).
*   **Key Content**: Full transcript, detailed summary, editable metadata fields (geo-tagging, temporal, dialect, general tags - Requirement 2291), story playback controls.
*   **Navigation**: From `My Stories Page`; To `My Stories Page`, `Export / Share Options`.

### Export / Share Options
*   **Purpose**: Presents export formats (PDF, Podcast, Timeline) and manages explicit consent for public sharing (Requirement 2293, 2290).
*   **Key Content**: Checkboxes/radio buttons for export formats. Clear GDPR consent form for public sharing, including opt-in confirmation (Requirement 2290).
*   **Navigation**: From `Story Detail / Edit Page`; To `Story Detail / Edit Page`, `My Stories Page` (after confirmation).

### Public Archive Page
*   **Purpose**: Allows public users to browse stories consented for public sharing (Requirement 2295).
*   **Key Content**: Browseable list of public stories (titles, authors, summaries, tags). Search and filter options.
*   **Navigation**: From `Landing Page`; To `Public Story View Page`, `Login Page` / `Registration Page`.

### Public Story View Page
*   **Purpose**: Displays full content of a single publicly consented story (Requirement 2295).
*   **Key Content**: Full transcript, summary, public metadata, author (if shared). No editing or export options.
*   **Navigation**: From `Public Archive Page`; To `Public Archive Page`.

## Design Specification (PRIMARY DESIGN SOURCE)
## Design System Overview

Storycatcher II's design philosophy centers on privacy, intuition, and accessibility. The interface will be clean, guided, and trustworthy, reflecting the application's commitment to local-first data handling and GDPR compliance (Requirements 2289, 2290). The design aims for a user-friendly and efficient experience, empowering users to easily capture and manage personal narratives (Artifact 1, 2).

The design language will be clear and unobtrusive, prioritizing content and user interaction. It will project reliability and security, essential for a platform handling sensitive personal stories. A modular, component-based architecture (leveraging React.js, Artifact 9) will ensure consistency, reusability, and maintainability across the application. Components will be organized to support efficient development and consistent user experience.

## Visual Design Elements

A color palette will be defined to convey trust and clarity, using a limited set of primary and accent colors. Neutral tones will dominate for readability, with strategic use of accent colors to highlight interactive elements and feedback (e.g., success, error states, Requirement 2298).

A clear and readable typography system will be established, with distinct hierarchies for titles, headings, body text, and UI labels. This ensures content legibility and guides user attention. A consistent spacing system and a responsive grid will be used to ensure visual balance, readability, and adaptability across various screen sizes, supporting intuitive layout of information and components.

A set of clear, intuitive icons will be designed or selected to represent actions (e.g., record, stop, save, share) and content types, enhancing usability and reducing cognitive load (e.g., for story management, Requirement 2292; export/sharing, Requirement 2293).

## Component Library

### UI component specifications and variations
*   **Authentication Forms**: Input fields, buttons, and validation messages for user registration and login (Requirement 2285).
*   **Audio Recording Controls**: Buttons for start, stop, pause, and indicators for recording status and duration (Requirements 2288, 2300).
*   **Text Displays**: Areas for displaying real-time voice-to-text transcripts, AI-generated summaries, and guiding questions (Requirement 2288).
*   **Story List/Grid Views**: Components for displaying archived stories with metadata (title, tags) (Requirement 2292).
*   **Story Detail/Edit Forms**: Input fields for editing story title, description, and applying metadata tags (geo-tagging, temporal, dialect, general tags) (Requirements 2291, 2292).
*   **Export/Share Options**: Checkboxes, dropdowns, and buttons for selecting export formats (PDF, Podcast, Timeline) and managing sharing consent (Requirements 2293, 2290).
*   **Language Selector**: A component for switching UI languages (German/English) (Requirement 2294).
*   **Consent Dialogs**: Explicit opt-in prompts for data handling and public sharing (Requirement 2290).

### Interactive states and behaviors
Components will include defined states for idle, hover, active, disabled, loading, and error (Requirements 2288, 2298). Form inputs will include validation feedback.

### Component usage guidelines and best practices
Guidelines will ensure consistent application of components across the UI, promoting reusability and a unified user experience.

### Accessibility and responsive design considerations
All components will be designed to be accessible, supporting keyboard navigation, screen readers, and multilingual content (Requirement 2294). Responsive design principles will ensure optimal display and functionality across diverse devices.

## Design Patterns and Guidelines

### Interaction design patterns and user flows
User interactions will follow established flows to provide a predictable and efficient experience. Key flows, such as the `Interactive Story Capture Flow`, will guide the user through recording, processing, and AI interaction (Requirement 2288).

```mermaid
graph TD
    A["User - Dashboard"] --> B["Start New Story / Record"];
    B --> C{"Microphone Access Granted?"};
    C -- "No" --> D["Request Microphone Permission"];
    D -- "Granted" --> E("Frontend - Activate MediaRecorder");
    D -- "Denied" --> F["Display Mic Access Error"];
    C -- "Yes" --> E;
    E --> G["Frontend - Display Recording UI"];

    subgraph "Interactive Recording Loop"
        G --> H["User - Speak into Microphone"];
        H --> I["Frontend - Capture Audio Segment"];
        I --> J["User - Stop Recording Segment"];
        J --> K("Frontend - Send Audio to Backend");
        K --> L("Backend - Local-First STT Engine");
        L --> M("Backend - AI Interview Logic");
        M --> N["Backend - Send Transcript / Analysis / Question"];
        N --> O["Frontend - Store Data Locally IndexedDB"];
        O --> P["Frontend - Display Analysis / New Question"];
        P --> Q{"Continue Recording?"};
        Q -- "Yes" --> G;
    end

    Q -- "No / Finalize" --> R["Frontend - Finalize Story"];
    R --> S("Backend - Story Finalization");
    S --> T["Frontend - Story Archived Confirmation"];
    F --> X["User - End Session"];
    T --> X;
```

### Navigation and information architecture principles
Navigation will be intuitive, allowing users to easily move between primary sections. A clear hierarchy will be maintained.

### Form design and data input patterns
Forms for registration (Requirement 2285) and metadata tagging (Requirement 2291) will feature clear labels, input validation, and assistive text to guide users.

### Error handling and feedback mechanisms
Comprehensive error handling (Requirement 2298) will provide clear, immediate feedback for issues such as microphone access denial, API call failures, or processing errors. UI states will gracefully transition, and user-friendly messages will guide recovery or suggest support.

## User Flows
## User Flows Overview

This document outlines the key user journeys within Storycatcher II, a privacy-centric application for capturing and managing personal stories. The purpose of these flows is to visualize the step-by-step interactions between the user and the system, highlighting critical paths, decision points, and system responses. Flows are categorized to provide a clear understanding of core functionalities, user onboarding, and data management processes, all strictly adhering to the requirements outlined in the project artifacts.

## Primary User Journey Flows

### User Registration and Login Flow (Requirement 2285)
This flow details the initial entry point for users, allowing new users to register securely and existing users to log in.

```mermaid
graph TD
    A["User - Landing Page"] --> B{"Has Account?"};
    B -- "No" --> C["Registration Page"];
    C --> D{"Enter Details / Register"};
    D --> E("Backend - Register User");
    E -- "Success" --> F["Login Page"];
    B -- "Yes" --> F;
    F --> G{"Enter Credentials / Login"};
    G --> H("Backend - Authenticate User");
    H -- "Success" --> I["Dashboard / My Stories Page"];
    H -- "Failure" --> F;
    E -- "Failure" --> C;
```

### Interactive Story Capture Flow (Requirements 2288, 2300, 2287, 2286)
This core flow describes how users record audio, receive AI-guided questions, and process story segments, integrating microphone access, local-first STT, and AI assistance.

